questions.individual_instructions:
Section A (18 marks)
For each question from 1 to 9, four options are given. One of them is the correct answer.
Make your choice (1, 2, 3 or 4) and shade your answer on the Optical Answer Sheet.
questions.main_question_text: The diagram below shows the human digestive system.

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram of the human digestive system with parts A (mouth/esophagus), B (stomach), C (small intestine), and D (large intestine) labeled.

parts.question_text: Which of the following statements is correct?
options: Digestion is completed in part C.
No digestion takes place in part A.
No digestive juice is found in part B.
Digested food is absorbed into the blood in part D.
parts.correct_answer: Digestion is completed in part C.

questions.main_question_text: Study the table below on human body systems. Which of the following is correct?

diagram_info.diagram_description: Table showing human body systems, organs, and their functions, with four rows presenting different combinations.

options: Skeletal Brain To protect our main organs.
Muscular Muscles To give our body its shape
Circulatory Heart To pump blood to the rest of the body.
Respiratory Blood To transport waste materials away from different parts of the body.
parts.correct_answer: Circulatory Heart To pump blood to the rest of the body.

questions.main_question_text: A, B, C, D and E are organs in the digestive system. The graph below shows the amount of undigested food leaving each organ after a meal. Which of the following is correct?

diagram_info.diagram_description: Bar graph showing the amount of undigested food leaving organs B, C, D, and E in the digestive system. X-axis shows organs B, C, D, E. Y-axis shows amount of undigested food leaving each organ.

options: Mouth: A, Gullet: D, Small intestine: B, Large intestine: E
Mouth: B, Gullet: C, Small intestine: D, Large intestine: A
Mouth: E, Gullet: B, Small intestine: C, Large intestine: A
Mouth: B, Gullet: E, Small intestine: A, Large intestine: D
parts.correct_answer: Mouth: A, Gullet: D, Small intestine: B, Large intestine: E

questions.main_question_text: Alex and Kaylyn made the following statements about substance X which is in a container. Which of the following tests can help determine which student is correct?

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram showing a beaker with substance X, Alex claiming it's a solid, and Kaylyn claiming it's a liquid.

options: To find out if substance X has mass.
To find out if substance X can be compressed.
To find out if substance X has a definite shape.
To find out if substance X has a definite volume.
parts.correct_answer: To find out if substance X has a definite shape.

questions.main_question_text: An experiment was set up as shown below using a sealed metal container which holds 60 cm³ of water and 30 cm³ of air. 10 cm³ of water was removed from the container through the tap. Which of the following correctly shows the amount of air in the container at the end of the experiment and the explanation of the results?

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram of a sealed metal container showing 30 cm³ of air, 60 cm³ of water, a pump, and a tap.

options: 30 cm³ Air can be compressed.
30 cm³ Air has no definite volume.
40 cm³ Air can be compressed.
40 cm³ Air has no definite volume.
parts.correct_answer: 40 cm³ Air has no definite volume.

questions.main_question_text: The diagram below shows two objects, X and Y, placed on a beam balance. Based on the observation above, which statement is correct?

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram of a beam balance with object X on the left pan and object Y on the right pan. The pan with object X is lower than the pan with object Y, indicating X has a greater mass.

options: Y has a greater mass than X.
Y has a greater volume than X.
Both X and Y are made of the same material.
Objects with smaller mass, have smaller volume.
parts.correct_answer: Y has a greater mass than X.

questions.main_question_text: Which one of the following is a source of light?

diagram_info.diagram_description: Image of a lit lamp.
Image of a mirror.
Image of an apple.
Image of the moon (crescent shape).

options: a lit lamp
a mirror
an apple
the moon

questions.main_question_text:
Kaelyn conducted an experiment and realised that she can see light through the holes of the cardboards when they are aligned. However, when one of the cardboards is shifted slightly, she no longer sees the light.
Which is the correct reason for her observation?

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram showing Kaelyn's experiment setup with a torchlight emitting light towards three aligned cardboards with holes, and Kaelyn observing from the other side. Labels include 'torchlight', 'cardboards', and 'Kaelyn'.

options: Light can be reflected.
Light cannot be blocked.
Light is a form of energy.
Light travels in a straight line.
parts.correct_answer: Light travels in a straight line.

questions.main_question_text: Study the diagram below. How is Darwin able to see the picture?

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram showing Darwin looking at a picture on an easel, with a light source illuminating the scene.

options: The picture gives off light and enters his eyes.
The light reflects the picture and enters his eyes.
The light enters his eyes and reflects on the picture.
The light falls on the picture and gets reflected into his eyes.
parts.correct_answer: The light falls on the picture and gets reflected into his eyes.

global_instructions: For questions 10 to 14, write your answers in the spaces provided.
The number of marks available is shown in bracket [ ] at the end of each question or part question.

questions.main_question_text: Larry carried out an experiment to find out how the size of the food cube affects the time taken for it to be completely digested. Each set-up contains the same amount of digestive juices and the same amount of food.

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram showing set-up X with a beaker containing 20 ml of digestive juices and a large food cube.
Diagram showing set-up Y with a beaker containing 20 ml of digestive juices and small food cubes.
Table showing the time taken for food to be completely digested for Set-up X (large food cube: 2 hours) and Set-up Y (small food cube: 1 hour).

parts.question_text: What is the changed variable in this experiment?
Based on the information given, what is the relationship between the time taken for all the food to be completely digested and the size of the food cube?
Explain how chewing food helps to digest food faster.

questions.main_question_text: Alex and Ben are preparing for a shadow puppet show. Below are the items that have been provided to them to stage the puppet show.

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram showing items for a shadow puppet show: satay sticks, cardboard, and white cloth for the screen.

parts.question_text: They realise that one item is not provided. What is the item?
Give a reason why the cardboard is used to make puppets.

questions.main_question_text:
The diagram below shows a setup used in a dark room to measure the amount of light that could pass through different materials, P, Q and R.
The table below shows the amount of light that passed through different materials, P, Q and R.
The picture below shows a pair of sunglasses.

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram of an experimental setup in a dark room showing a light source, a material placed in its path, and a light sensor connected to a datalogger detecting light that passes through the material.

Table showing the amount of light detected by a light sensor after passing through different materials (P, Q, R) and with no material. The data is: No material = 100 units, P = 0 units, Q = 60 units, R = 99 units.
Diagram of a pair of sunglasses with the lens part labeled as 'part M'.

parts.question_text: Based on the results, which material P, Q or R. would be most suitable to make Part M of the sunglasses? Explain your answer.
What will happen to the amount of light that passes through if materials P and R are placed together?

questions.main_question_text: Derrick inverted two identical plastic cups, A and B, into a basin of water as shown in the diagram below. He pierced a hole at the base of one of the plastic cups.

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram showing two identical plastic cups, A and B, inverted in a basin of water. Cup A has trapped air, while cup B shows air escaping, indicating a hole at its base. Labels include 'base', 'plastic cup A', 'plastic cup B', and 'a basin of water'.

parts.question_text: Based on the results shown above, which plastic cup, A or B, is more likely to have a hole at its base? Explain your answer.

questions.main_question_text: Mr Tan filled a container to the brim with marbles as shown in the diagram below. Next, he tried to pour some water into the container.

diagram_info.diagram_description: Diagram of a cylindrical container filled to the brim with marbles, with labels 'container' and 'marble'.

parts.question_text: (a) Explain why Mr Tan is able to pour water into the container even though the marbles were filled to the brim.
(b) Besides taking up space, state another property of liquid which enables the water to be poured into the container of marbles.
